
🔐 1. Security (Left Panel)
Authentication & Authorization

  What: Verifying who the user is (AuthN) and what they can do (AuthZ)
  What we use: JWT tokens / OAuth 2.0 + Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)
  Why: Every API call must be validated. Without this, anyone can post as anyone else
  Interview point: "Auth & IAM" service at the bottom handles this centrally

Encryption

  What: Data protection in transit and at rest
  What we use: TLS/HTTPS in transit, AES-256 at rest
  Why: Protects passwords, DMs, personal data from interception

🌐 2. CDN (Content Delivery Network)

What: Geographically distributed servers that cache static content
What we use: Cloudflare / AWS CloudFront
Why:

Serves images, videos, JS/CSS from nearest server to user
Reduces latency dramatically (Delhi user gets content from Mumbai, not US)
Reduces load on your origin servers


Interview point: Media (profile pics, tweet images) is served via CDN, NOT your main server


💻 3. Client Layer
Two clients shown:
ClientNotesWeb AppReact/Next.js, communicates over HTTPSMobile AppiOS/Android, same APIs

Both communicate via HTTPS to the Load Balancer
Why HTTPS? Encrypted channel — prevents man-in-the-middle attacks

⚖️ 4. Load Balancer

Algorithm: Round Robin
Type: Layer 7 (Application Layer)
What we use: AWS ALB / NGINX
Why Round Robin? Distributes requests evenly across server instances
Why Layer 7?

Can inspect HTTP headers, URLs, cookies
Can route /api/tweet to Tweet service, /api/search to Search service
Supports sticky sessions, health checks, SSL termination


Interview point: Layer 4 (TCP) is faster but dumb — Layer 7 is smarter and routes intelligently

🚪 5. API Gateway

What: Single entry point for all microservice calls
What we use: AWS API Gateway / Kong
Responsibilities:

Rate limiting (prevent spam/DDoS)
Authentication validation (checks JWT before forwarding)
Request routing to correct microservice
Logging & monitoring


Why: Without it, clients would need to know every microservice address — tight coupling


⚙️ 6. Microservices
Tweet CRUD Service

Create, Read, Update, Delete tweets
Writes to Tweet Content DB
On write → pushes to Message Queue for async fanout
Why separate service? Most trafficked feature — can scale independently

Reply CRUD Service

Handles replies to tweets
Has its own Replies DB
Connected via CDC (Change Data Capture)
Why CDC? Captures DB changes as events without polling — efficient real-time sync

Search Service

Full-text search on tweets
Uses Elasticsearch as its database
Why Elasticsearch? Built for full-text search, handles fuzzy matching, extremely fast at scale
Fanout on read label means search results are assembled at query time

Timeline Service

Builds the home feed for users
Reads from Timeline Cache (Redis)
Why cache? Rebuilding feed for every request from DB would be too slow for millions of users

Profile Service

Manages user profiles
Reads/writes User Data DB and Following Data DB
Following data is likely a Graph DB (Neo4j) or adjacency list — naturally models relationships

Auth & IAM Service

Identity and Access Management
Validates tokens for all other services
What we use: Keycloak / AWS Cognito / custom JWT service


📨 7. Message Queue

What: Async messaging between services
What we use: Apache Kafka / RabbitMQ
Why:

When you post a tweet, you have 10M followers — you can't update all timelines synchronously
Queue decouples the Tweet service from Timeline Fanout
If fanout is slow/down, tweets still get saved


📤 8. Timeline Fanout Service

What: Pushes new tweets to followers' timelines
Strategy shown: Fanout on Write (Push model)
How it works:

Tweet posted → goes to Message Queue
Fanout service reads queue
Writes tweet ID to each follower's Timeline Cache (Redis)


Interview tradeoff:

Fanout on Write = fast reads, expensive writes (bad for celebrities with 50M followers)
Fanout on Read = slow reads, cheap writes
Hybrid: Use fanout-on-write for normal users, fanout-on-read for celebrities


